1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:08,550 --> 00:00:11,950
Bro, you definitely haven't had enough yet.

3
00:00:13,050 --> 00:00:14,650
I haven't even beaten my personal record yet.

4
00:00:21,200 --> 00:00:21,880
Ozzak!

5
00:00:23,550 --> 00:00:25,550
You're drinking during work hours again.

6
00:00:25,650 --> 00:00:27,450
Hello, Marcelka.

7
00:00:27,850 --> 00:00:29,620
Tomas, good day.

8
00:00:29,950 --> 00:00:31,350
You put up with this.

9
00:00:31,950 --> 00:00:36,450
Next week is Premium Lager Days and Ozzak is defending the Golden Kidney there.

10
00:00:37,150 --> 00:00:39,850
So I made an exception and let him train in the shop.

11
00:00:40,250 --> 00:00:41,250
Train?

12
00:00:42,150 --> 00:00:45,050
The Golden Kidney is the top prize in the beer pentathlon.

13
00:00:45,950 --> 00:00:47,150
He's training for the marathon right now.

14
00:00:48,750 --> 00:00:50,850
What does this have to do with running?

15
00:00:51,550 --> 00:00:54,550
It's about how many beers you can drink before you have to go to the bathroom.

16
00:00:54,680 --> 00:00:55,200
Disgusting.

17
00:00:55,400 --> 00:00:57,300
You haven't seen the freestyle event yet.

18
00:00:57,740 --> 00:00:58,700
I mean Ozzak.

19
00:00:58,860 --> 00:00:59,940
I mean the competition.

20
00:01:00,650 --> 00:01:02,440
Thank God for the pentathlon.

21
00:01:02,750 --> 00:01:04,980
When he did the Nordic combined, it was worse.

22
00:01:05,350 --> 00:01:06,550
That's drinking on skis?

23
00:01:08,060 --> 00:01:10,480
A liter of vodka, sauna, and then hammer throw.

24
00:01:10,480 --> 00:01:11,500
Prague '17.

25
00:01:14,450 --> 00:01:17,790
Will he be able to look after the shop in this state when we're in Bruntal?

26
00:01:17,950 --> 00:01:18,650
Where?

27
00:01:19,550 --> 00:01:20,280
In Bruntal.

28
00:01:20,350 --> 00:01:22,650
I've arranged a concert for you there next week.

29
00:01:23,750 --> 00:01:26,350
Jesus Mary, woman, have you lost your mind?

30
00:01:27,090 --> 00:01:27,630
Allow me.

31
00:01:27,690 --> 00:01:30,390
You don't go to Bruntal, they have the worst audience.

32
00:01:30,690 --> 00:01:32,090
What kind of nonsense is that?

33
00:01:32,110 --> 00:01:33,610
There are people there like everywhere else.

34
00:01:33,970 --> 00:01:34,990
Everyone knows it.

35
00:01:35,170 --> 00:01:37,970
Even Vlada Hron says so here in his Showbiz Calendar.

36
00:01:38,190 --> 00:01:38,730
Where?

37
00:01:38,730 --> 00:01:40,470
In the Showbiz Calendar.

38
00:01:40,850 --> 00:01:42,950
It's his handbook for regional artists.

39
00:01:43,050 --> 00:01:45,050
You can see it right on the first page.

40
00:01:45,350 --> 00:01:47,650
Three golden rules of Vlada Hron.

41
00:01:47,850 --> 00:01:49,550
Lip-sync is a safe bet,

42
00:01:49,850 --> 00:01:53,880
anything for television, and never take Bruntal.

43
00:01:55,850 --> 00:02:01,950
There are terrible things written about Bruntal in here.

44
00:02:33,350 --> 00:02:42,840
Tomas, I spoke with the mayor and he said Mr. Hron is getting back at them for that unfortunate misunderstanding after his concert.

45
00:02:42,950 --> 00:02:44,550
What misunderstanding?

46
00:02:44,850 --> 00:02:51,590
He wouldn't say, but he emphasized that they're currently not asphalting anywhere and feathers are extremely scarce.

47
00:02:52,050 --> 00:02:53,650
And that's supposed to calm me down?

48
00:02:54,550 --> 00:02:59,150
Bruntal people are very tough and all my songs are about love.

49
00:02:59,850 --> 00:03:08,310
Bruntal's happiest period was in 1964 when the army experimentally added LSD to the water supply.

50
00:03:08,310 --> 00:03:11,350
But things must have improved since then.

51
00:03:11,550 --> 00:03:11,710
Yeah?

52
00:03:11,870 --> 00:03:15,810
In '84 they made Mencik cry there.

53
00:03:15,990 --> 00:03:17,670
But they're really looking forward to you.

54
00:03:17,770 --> 00:03:20,730
They even sent a deposit just for a promise of a performance.

55
00:03:22,750 --> 00:03:23,360
Socks?

56
00:03:23,360 --> 00:03:25,760
Sixty pairs of socks in dove grey.

57
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:27,540
They're quite nice.

58
00:03:27,640 --> 00:03:28,400
And fireproof.

59
00:03:29,710 --> 00:03:30,910
Are you kidding?

60
00:03:31,030 --> 00:03:31,950
It's a rough region.

61
00:03:33,450 --> 00:03:35,750
And they also included an information brochure.

62
00:03:37,650 --> 00:03:41,040
And this would be your first district town, not counting Zlin.

63
00:03:41,040 --> 00:03:43,460
That was a big lesson, Marcelka, a big lesson.

64
00:03:43,640 --> 00:03:46,300
Well, see, and in Bruntal they'll let you sing.

65
00:03:46,440 --> 00:03:49,240
They nearly tore my arms off, I had to promise them an encore.

66
00:03:49,560 --> 00:03:50,080
Really?

67
00:03:50,950 --> 00:03:54,250
Tomas, I can feel it in my bones that this will be a success.

68
00:03:54,480 --> 00:03:56,280
As long as we don't underestimate the preparation.

69
00:03:56,280 --> 00:04:00,150
The journey to Bruntal takes somewhere between six and twenty hours.

70
00:04:00,650 --> 00:04:01,850
How come?

71
00:04:02,250 --> 00:04:05,430
The mayor said it depends on whether it's the rainy season.

72
00:04:06,050 --> 00:04:08,940
And when is the rainy season in Bruntal?

73
00:04:09,150 --> 00:04:09,950
All year round.

74
00:04:10,150 --> 00:04:11,950
Well, except for April Two.

75
00:04:13,150 --> 00:04:14,140
What's April Two?

76
00:04:14,550 --> 00:04:15,650
That's what they call July.

77
00:04:20,350 --> 00:04:23,850
I don't understand how you can keep drinking after twenty beers.

78
00:04:24,450 --> 00:04:25,320
I'm doing a cooldown.

79
00:04:25,550 --> 00:04:26,050
How many?

80
00:04:40,650 --> 00:04:41,450
About a minute.

81
00:04:42,950 --> 00:04:44,260
About a minute?

82
00:04:44,260 --> 00:04:45,620
What do you mean about a minute?

83
00:04:45,660 --> 00:04:46,520
What's that supposed to be?

84
00:04:46,850 --> 00:04:48,850
Damn it, Mambo, you're a lousy timekeeper.

85
00:04:49,080 --> 00:04:49,640
48.

86
00:04:50,380 --> 00:04:51,200
There you go.

87
00:04:51,750 --> 00:04:52,450
That's more like it.

88
00:04:53,650 --> 00:04:54,250
Forty.

89
00:04:54,850 --> 00:04:55,550
Again.

90
00:04:55,650 --> 00:04:57,050
But without me.

91
00:04:57,150 --> 00:04:59,240
Hey, bro clearly told you to time me.

92
00:04:59,240 --> 00:05:00,300
But he didn't say how many times.

93
00:05:00,480 --> 00:05:01,540
Crap, this won't be good.

94
00:05:01,740 --> 00:05:02,940
Seems fine to me.

95
00:05:03,020 --> 00:05:03,180
No!

96
00:05:03,850 --> 00:05:06,650
The guy from Pilsen did the half-pint in under thirty.

97
00:05:07,230 --> 00:05:07,670
Radim.

98
00:05:10,350 --> 00:05:10,790
Hey.

99
00:05:12,250 --> 00:05:13,250
Practicing the straw?

100
00:05:17,150 --> 00:05:18,050
Tomas isn't here.

101
00:05:18,290 --> 00:05:19,710
He went to buy some dentures.

102
00:05:19,870 --> 00:05:20,990
He'll be back in a moment.

103
00:05:21,270 --> 00:05:22,630
Damn, and I have to run.

104
00:05:23,250 --> 00:05:24,450
Could you help me?

105
00:05:24,850 --> 00:05:27,790
I'm going to the employment office, I'm not sure if I filled out their form correctly.

106
00:05:28,350 --> 00:05:30,550
Especially the job requirements section here.

107
00:05:30,570 --> 00:05:32,890
What's so hard about writing "waitress"?

108
00:05:33,270 --> 00:05:34,650
She doesn't want the job, does she?

109
00:05:34,670 --> 00:05:35,730
Something like at the Badger.

110
00:05:36,050 --> 00:05:37,670
Requirements for working hours.

111
00:05:37,670 --> 00:05:44,650
Seventeen hours max. Well, that max can be minimum, every other Sunday work fully clothed.

112
00:05:46,150 --> 00:05:47,090
Is it excessive?

113
00:05:47,090 --> 00:05:47,790
No.

114
00:05:47,990 --> 00:05:48,690
Great.

115
00:05:49,750 --> 00:05:51,830
I want a job, but a tough accountant.

116
00:05:52,250 --> 00:05:52,950
Mambo, let's go.

117
00:05:53,840 --> 00:05:54,540
Now!

118
00:05:56,150 --> 00:05:56,860
I'm off then.

119
00:05:57,150 --> 00:05:59,650
Good luck and don't let them rattle you.

120
00:05:59,950 --> 00:06:00,480
Why?

121
00:06:00,650 --> 00:06:02,300
At the employment office they always had a laugh at Mambo's expense.

122
00:06:02,300 --> 00:06:02,740
Really?

123
00:06:03,120 --> 00:06:06,860
I wanted to confirm my average income and they sent me bus papers by mail.

124
00:06:07,060 --> 00:06:07,500
I see.

125
00:06:08,080 --> 00:06:12,300
At first I wanted to yell at them, but then I realized the bus actually comes in handy sometimes.

126
00:06:12,420 --> 00:06:14,000
There has to be chaos at the government offices.

127
00:06:14,160 --> 00:06:18,160
If they had things in order at social services, I could forget about those guide dog allowances.

128
00:06:19,210 --> 00:06:23,610
Well, it's not much, five grand a year, but they throw in a bag of really good kibble.

129
00:06:24,200 --> 00:06:25,700
Aren't you worried they'll catch on?

130
00:06:25,920 --> 00:06:28,960
In five years they only came to check once, and luckily in summer.

131
00:06:29,120 --> 00:06:30,820
You pretended to be on vacation.

132
00:06:30,840 --> 00:06:34,540
No, Lexa let them in, but luckily I was wearing sunglasses.

133
00:06:34,800 --> 00:06:37,180
So all I had to do was bump into the wardrobe a few times and yell "Barik."

134
00:06:37,850 --> 00:06:39,850
Now I get the tram for free too.

135
00:06:40,950 --> 00:06:41,350
Time!

136
00:06:41,730 --> 00:06:42,130
Pardon?

137
00:06:43,430 --> 00:06:43,990
I have a time.

138
00:06:46,150 --> 00:06:47,850
Thirty... six.

139
00:06:52,950 --> 00:06:54,950
The guy would have downed the half-pint in that time.

140
00:06:55,160 --> 00:06:55,840
So bye.

141
00:07:14,020 --> 00:07:15,100
Jesus, uncle, what happened?

142
00:07:15,100 --> 00:07:18,150
Nothing, I was practicing triple-chug and the pint glass slipped.

143
00:07:18,520 --> 00:07:20,080
Aren't you overdoing the training a bit?

144
00:07:20,260 --> 00:07:21,920
Listen girl, talent isn't everything.

145
00:07:22,160 --> 00:07:23,880
I just don't want you to be overtrained.

146
00:07:24,060 --> 00:07:24,880
You're probably right.

147
00:07:25,750 --> 00:07:30,850
Maybe I'll call Pitl and tell him I'm skipping synchronized drinking this year and just doing the pentathlon.

148
00:07:33,390 --> 00:07:34,010
Brutal.

149
00:07:34,450 --> 00:07:35,690
Uncle, what's wrong with you?

150
00:07:35,970 --> 00:07:37,270
I'm kind of nervous, you know.

151
00:07:37,530 --> 00:07:38,430
About what?

152
00:07:38,430 --> 00:07:40,490
You've won the Golden Kidney four times in a row.

153
00:07:40,650 --> 00:07:42,650
But this year they've allowed professionals to compete.

154
00:07:42,810 --> 00:07:43,430
What professionals?

155
00:07:43,690 --> 00:07:45,750
Fibbinger is coming, he drinks first league in Germany.

156
00:07:45,770 --> 00:07:46,610
So do you.

157
00:07:46,730 --> 00:07:48,430
We don't have a league here, Ivuska.

158
00:07:48,790 --> 00:07:50,710
We're all registered as amateurs.

159
00:07:50,910 --> 00:07:51,350
What?

160
00:07:51,850 --> 00:07:53,750
Fibbinger is a pro from the Fazby League.

161
00:07:54,350 --> 00:07:58,850
They say a week before a meet he sleeps buried in salt to build up a thirst.

162
00:07:59,450 --> 00:08:01,290
Wait, he actually makes a living doing this?

163
00:08:01,550 --> 00:08:03,550
Well you know, Germany, they've always been ahead.

164
00:08:04,850 --> 00:08:05,850
And his conditions.

165
00:08:06,250 --> 00:08:08,150
Special training pubs.

166
00:08:08,350 --> 00:08:11,820
Training camp at Oktoberfest and equipment you can only dream of.

167
00:08:11,820 --> 00:08:12,940
Teflon straws.

168
00:08:13,450 --> 00:08:14,270
And me?

169
00:08:15,450 --> 00:08:17,350
Three old shot glasses, a straw you used, and a paper bag instead of a starting pistol.

170
00:08:19,790 --> 00:08:20,870
And Mambo keeps my time!

171
00:08:30,550 --> 00:08:36,350
So Mr. Burda, that's a 500 crown fine for yelling at government offices.

172
00:08:37,850 --> 00:08:39,450
Pay at the cashier's window.

173
00:08:39,450 --> 00:08:39,850
Yeah.

174
00:08:44,450 --> 00:08:45,450
Next!

175
00:08:51,350 --> 00:08:52,950
Come in, have a seat.

176
00:08:54,450 --> 00:08:57,240
I'm out of work, so I thought you could help me.

177
00:08:57,450 --> 00:08:58,960
Are you a college graduate?

178
00:08:58,960 --> 00:08:59,260
No.

179
00:09:00,350 --> 00:09:01,890
That's a relief.

180
00:09:02,150 --> 00:09:02,930
Is this your first time here?

181
00:09:02,930 --> 00:09:03,030
Yeah.

182
00:09:04,150 --> 00:09:05,460
Sign this here for me.

183
00:09:05,460 --> 00:09:05,820
What is it?

184
00:09:06,650 --> 00:09:09,660
That you've been informed about the ban on yelling at government offices.

185
00:09:09,660 --> 00:09:09,820
I see.

186
00:09:10,650 --> 00:09:13,050
We've been having some problems with that lately.

187
00:09:15,150 --> 00:09:18,750
You really worked as the sole employee of a non-stop?

188
00:09:18,870 --> 00:09:19,030
Yeah.

189
00:09:20,150 --> 00:09:21,750
And you never closed?

190
00:09:22,350 --> 00:09:23,510
Once for 20 minutes.

191
00:09:23,650 --> 00:09:24,950
My son fell out of a window.

192
00:09:25,030 --> 00:09:26,190
For twenty minutes?

193
00:09:26,190 --> 00:09:29,550
Well, I had to go open the building for him, he couldn't reach the doorbells yet.

194
00:09:29,630 --> 00:09:30,190
I see.

195
00:09:32,050 --> 00:09:37,450
So, Mrs. Buckova, I'll register you in the computer now.

196
00:09:37,850 --> 00:09:43,390
Since it's your first time, you don't even know how much easier everything is now that we've been connected to ISSS.

197
00:09:43,390 --> 00:09:43,970
To what?

198
00:09:44,950 --> 00:09:47,450
Integrated System of State Administration.

199
00:09:47,450 --> 00:09:50,030
Look, it's all Greek to me too.

200
00:09:52,850 --> 00:09:54,250
It's like a big computer that knows everything.

201
00:09:54,550 --> 00:09:55,550
Absolutely everything?

202
00:09:55,750 --> 00:09:56,390
Absolutely.

203
00:09:56,750 --> 00:09:58,090
All the offices are on it now.

204
00:09:58,550 --> 00:10:01,750
From the veterinary administration to the land registry.

205
00:10:02,550 --> 00:10:05,410
Before, you had to run around to all of them yourself.

206
00:10:06,850 --> 00:10:11,550
And today all I need to do is type in your birth number and it pulls up everything about you.

207
00:10:13,350 --> 00:10:28,150
Whether you pay taxes, what social benefits you receive, whether you owe anything on health insurance, or what your milk yield is.

208
00:10:29,540 --> 00:10:30,340
One moment.

209
00:10:33,750 --> 00:10:39,850
Vera, hey, Holstein cattle breeding charts showed up on my screen.

210
00:10:40,750 --> 00:10:41,650
Yours too?

211
00:10:42,350 --> 00:10:44,050
Actually, how do I get rid of it?

212
00:10:45,050 --> 00:10:45,950
I can't.

213
00:10:46,050 --> 00:10:48,210
Ah, okay then.

214
00:10:48,450 --> 00:10:49,050
Bye.

215
00:10:50,650 --> 00:10:55,830
So, please, fill this out and then come back.

216
00:10:56,150 --> 00:10:56,550
Thank you.

217
00:10:57,310 --> 00:10:58,190
Bye.

218
00:11:08,850 --> 00:11:15,890
In recent years, with the support of the European Union, the devastated landscape has been restored to its original character.

219
00:11:15,890 --> 00:11:16,930
The Armageddon summit?

220
00:11:17,250 --> 00:11:19,930
No, that's the Bruntal region before recultivation.

221
00:11:19,930 --> 00:11:24,550
And now let's recall what Bruntal looked like before recultivation.

222
00:11:26,450 --> 00:11:27,450
Do you really have to?

223
00:11:28,650 --> 00:11:30,750
Marcelka already signed the contract.

224
00:11:32,250 --> 00:11:35,010
Malicious tongues claim that Bruntal people don't like to have fun.

225
00:11:35,350 --> 00:11:37,250
Nothing could be further from the truth.

226
00:11:37,750 --> 00:11:41,250
In Bruntal, some colorful pastimes were actually born.

227
00:11:41,650 --> 00:11:47,420
Besides hunting pregnant does, there's mainly the legendary race called the Silage Bullet.

228
00:11:47,420 --> 00:11:47,720
Dad?

229
00:11:47,760 --> 00:11:48,080
One moment.

230
00:11:48,400 --> 00:11:50,720
Why is it printed on the back of a funeral announcement?

231
00:11:50,920 --> 00:11:51,560
What?

232
00:11:52,220 --> 00:11:53,380
They say they're saving there.

233
00:11:55,450 --> 00:12:00,850
In archival footage we see a group of competitors gathering at the bottom of a silage pit.

234
00:12:01,250 --> 00:12:05,050
The hunters are already loaded, so we'll wait for the gunshot.

235
00:12:07,450 --> 00:12:08,550
I'm not going anywhere.

236
00:12:17,050 --> 00:12:19,060
Pardon, but you gave me the wrong form.

237
00:12:19,060 --> 00:12:19,640
Sorry.

238
00:12:20,350 --> 00:12:23,280
This says application for a long-distance pipeline construction permit.

239
00:12:23,750 --> 00:12:24,850
That's fine.

240
00:12:25,450 --> 00:12:27,050
But I don't want to build a pipeline.

241
00:12:27,150 --> 00:12:31,510
You know, when we order them through the system, sometimes different ones show up.

242
00:12:31,850 --> 00:12:34,730
So we don't make a big deal out of it and use what we have.

243
00:12:35,150 --> 00:12:37,950
And how am I supposed to fill it out?

244
00:12:38,750 --> 00:12:39,560
Normally.

245
00:12:40,150 --> 00:12:45,850
In the "cadastral area" box write your name, in "number of compressor stations" put the number of children.

246
00:12:46,050 --> 00:12:49,350
There's a sample filled out on the bulletin board on the second floor.

247
00:12:52,050 --> 00:12:53,050
Anything else?

248
00:12:59,950 --> 00:13:04,450
The last wolf in the Bruntal region was killed in 2008.

249
00:13:04,850 --> 00:13:07,950
The hunter was fourteen-year-old Ingo Wovs.

250
00:13:09,650 --> 00:13:11,150
Weapon used?

251
00:13:12,350 --> 00:13:12,850
A flail.

252
00:13:19,950 --> 00:13:23,620
I should probably stop reading this or I'll dream about the Silage Bullet.

253
00:13:27,250 --> 00:13:29,440
Come on bro, don't do this to me!

254
00:13:29,750 --> 00:13:31,240
I seriously can't train here!

255
00:13:31,550 --> 00:13:35,250
Sorry, can't you see my nerves are shot?

256
00:13:37,350 --> 00:13:38,650
Fine, I'll leave the sprint for morning.

257
00:13:39,100 --> 00:13:40,440
I'll set up a track for the triple-chug.

258
00:13:40,440 --> 00:13:43,550
Bruntal is scaring me more and more.

259
00:13:44,950 --> 00:13:46,450
Klistak is from Bruntal.

260
00:13:46,850 --> 00:13:48,460
He could tell you what it's like there.

261
00:13:48,650 --> 00:13:50,750
I'd rather not hear anything more.

262
00:13:51,250 --> 00:13:52,740
Well, he doesn't say much anyway.

263
00:13:53,050 --> 00:13:57,050
He just sits there, drinks his little beer, and draws frogs with teeth.

264
00:13:59,550 --> 00:14:00,050
And here we go.

265
00:14:15,450 --> 00:14:17,050
You drank my track.

266
00:14:18,150 --> 00:14:21,850
I haven't seen a triple-chug like that in a long time.

267
00:14:22,250 --> 00:14:24,450
This is what government administration does to a person.

268
00:14:43,250 --> 00:14:45,550
Just packing a few things for the trip.

269
00:14:46,850 --> 00:14:48,330
Marcelka, I've made up my mind.

270
00:14:48,650 --> 00:14:50,150
I'm not going to Bruntal.

271
00:14:50,550 --> 00:14:51,950
You talked to Hron, didn't you?

272
00:14:52,450 --> 00:14:55,450
I went to see him, but someone hit him with a flail.

273
00:14:56,450 --> 00:14:57,550
So he's in the ICU.

274
00:14:58,150 --> 00:15:00,030
Tomas, why are you stressing about this?

275
00:15:00,290 --> 00:15:02,270
Bruntal is a town like any other today.

276
00:15:02,550 --> 00:15:07,450
And did you know that the word Bruntal comes from the German Freudenthal, meaning happy valley?

277
00:15:07,650 --> 00:15:10,330
Yesterday they reported a cougar on the loose there.

278
00:15:10,330 --> 00:15:11,290
Don't be afraid of anything.

279
00:15:11,410 --> 00:15:12,610
I spoke with the mayor.

280
00:15:12,610 --> 00:15:16,450
He made a deal with the Wovs family and as soon as Ingo gets back from Prague, he'll sort it out.

281
00:15:16,550 --> 00:15:18,250
No, I'm not going.

282
00:15:19,350 --> 00:15:20,450
Have you read the contract?

283
00:15:20,550 --> 00:15:23,680
Of course, though there's one letter in it I don't recognize.

284
00:15:24,150 --> 00:15:26,550
That's a hard F, a regional specialty.

285
00:15:26,850 --> 00:15:30,160
Have you read the cancellation terms? They're on the other side.

286
00:15:30,450 --> 00:15:34,650
Under the names of the deceased's sons: Ingo, Viktor, and Wolf with families.

287
00:15:36,950 --> 00:15:40,450
The only acceptable excuse for canceling is illness.

288
00:15:40,450 --> 00:15:42,430
Even then you'd pay a forty thousand crown penalty.

289
00:15:43,150 --> 00:15:45,070
For God's sake, where would I get forty thousand?

290
00:15:45,170 --> 00:15:46,590
Or the equivalent in frog skins.

291
00:15:49,150 --> 00:15:51,610
Then call them and say I have the flu.

292
00:15:51,650 --> 00:15:55,750
Unfortunately, in the Bruntal region the flu isn't considered an illness but a sign of weakness.

293
00:15:57,450 --> 00:15:58,800
What counts as an illness there?

294
00:15:59,050 --> 00:16:00,350
A gunshot wound or a fracture.

295
00:16:00,750 --> 00:16:09,270
And regarding your last employment?

296
00:16:09,450 --> 00:16:10,550
I mined mud.

297
00:16:10,950 --> 00:16:11,750
Bruntal?

298
00:16:12,550 --> 00:16:15,250
And why did you leave?

299
00:16:15,850 --> 00:16:16,550
Ran out of mud.

300
00:16:21,250 --> 00:16:22,590
Excuse me for a minute.

301
00:16:22,950 --> 00:16:23,830
Is it necessary?

302
00:16:23,830 --> 00:16:23,930
Yes.

303
00:16:24,590 --> 00:16:27,030
This morning I found this envelope in your mailbox.

304
00:16:27,170 --> 00:16:27,830
And what about it?

305
00:16:28,010 --> 00:16:31,270
It contains a military draft order to a motorized rifle unit in Pribram.

306
00:16:31,770 --> 00:16:32,290
Wait.

307
00:16:33,550 --> 00:16:37,250
The computer apparently flagged you as an unconvicted white male.

308
00:16:37,250 --> 00:16:42,790
Under 25, in good physical condition.

309
00:16:43,250 --> 00:16:44,550
And what do we do about it?

310
00:16:45,150 --> 00:16:46,550
We'll cancel it.

311
00:16:47,750 --> 00:16:48,550
Yeah, right.

312
00:16:48,750 --> 00:16:50,620
You'd have to run around to a lot of places.

313
00:16:50,750 --> 00:16:54,580
The military administration, the registry, the gynecologist, and the district court.

314
00:16:54,580 --> 00:16:55,220
The gynecologist?

315
00:16:55,650 --> 00:16:57,350
To confirm that you're a woman.

316
00:16:57,850 --> 00:17:00,750
Today all you need to do is type in your birth number.

317
00:17:05,950 --> 00:17:06,590
Hymenoptera.

318
00:17:09,150 --> 00:17:10,150
Unfortunately.

319
00:17:12,150 --> 00:17:17,850
Military administration, registry, gynecologist, district court.

320
00:17:18,150 --> 00:17:18,850
Here you go.

321
00:17:22,750 --> 00:17:25,650
Vera, please, they showed up on my screen again.

322
00:17:26,450 --> 00:17:26,950
Yours too, huh.

323
00:17:28,450 --> 00:17:29,250
So that's that.

324
00:17:29,650 --> 00:17:38,880
Wait, Mrs. Buckova, please, at the gynecologist tell them to put your name under "estimated annual extraction volume" and your sex under "vegetation."

325
00:17:39,350 --> 00:17:41,650
So we don't have a mess here later, okay?

326
00:17:42,650 --> 00:17:44,650
Actually, Vera, how do I delete this?

327
00:17:45,150 --> 00:17:46,350
I can't.

328
00:17:46,450 --> 00:17:47,450
Ah, bye.

329
00:17:48,160 --> 00:17:59,890
Well, I'm off.

330
00:18:00,330 --> 00:18:02,010
So tomorrow, are you excited?

331
00:18:02,330 --> 00:18:03,590
Very, very excited.

332
00:18:03,710 --> 00:18:06,010
Tomorrow Bruntal, the day after maybe Ostrava.

333
00:18:06,210 --> 00:18:07,930
We'll hit the road at seven in the morning.

334
00:18:09,050 --> 00:18:11,640
We still need to practice putting on snow chains.

335
00:18:12,050 --> 00:18:14,150
But of course, it's May after all.

336
00:18:14,300 --> 00:18:15,540
February Two, Tomas.

337
00:18:22,050 --> 00:18:23,950
All right, bro, here I go!

338
00:18:24,150 --> 00:18:31,950
Break a leg, bro.

339
00:18:32,350 --> 00:18:35,420
Wait, you're not coming to watch?

340
00:18:35,420 --> 00:18:37,580
Mr. Pacovsky needs to get some sleep before the trip.

341
00:18:37,900 --> 00:18:41,180
But I'll come, of course I'll come, just let me stop by Simona's first.

342
00:18:41,400 --> 00:18:42,300
Is Mom home?

343
00:18:42,850 --> 00:18:45,550
She said she'd be back either at eight or when her shift ends.

344
00:18:47,550 --> 00:18:49,320
Then I'll wait for her.

345
00:18:49,320 --> 00:18:49,840
Bro.

346
00:18:50,650 --> 00:18:54,850
And if I win, you can hand me the flag when I drink the honorary beer.

347
00:18:54,920 --> 00:18:55,740
What is this?

348
00:18:56,550 --> 00:18:57,760
It's got the wrong colors right now.

349
00:18:57,950 --> 00:18:58,950
What do you mean wrong colors?

350
00:18:59,550 --> 00:19:01,250
White like foam, yellow like beer.

351
00:19:01,440 --> 00:19:01,960
I see.

352
00:19:03,050 --> 00:19:04,050
And the green?

353
00:19:05,450 --> 00:19:06,350
Green.

354
00:19:27,450 --> 00:19:28,050
Vera.

355
00:19:28,950 --> 00:19:30,950
Hey, I got a firearms license.

356
00:19:31,550 --> 00:19:32,650
Do you know what that is?

357
00:19:34,850 --> 00:19:35,530
A commendation?

358
00:19:35,530 --> 00:19:36,470
Well, great.

359
00:19:37,180 --> 00:19:38,380
Look, I was really freaked out.

360
00:19:38,950 --> 00:19:41,550
A commendation used to always be a transit visa.

361
00:19:42,450 --> 00:19:45,850
What, they sent that to you?

362
00:19:46,850 --> 00:19:49,050
A mining permit decision, yeah?

363
00:19:49,850 --> 00:19:52,250
Jesus, and what did you do?

364
00:19:53,350 --> 00:19:55,550
I have to go, I've got a client.

365
00:19:55,750 --> 00:19:58,500
Buckova, Simona, I don't want to go to the army.

366
00:19:58,950 --> 00:20:00,650
Okay, okay, okay.

367
00:20:01,950 --> 00:20:02,850
Jeez, but you'll have to go to the gynecologist again.

368
00:20:04,940 --> 00:20:06,960
The system sent the correct forms.

369
00:20:07,650 --> 00:20:12,150
They're white on black, but hopefully your gynecologist has a white pencil.

370
00:20:12,150 --> 00:20:24,180
What is it?

371
00:20:25,150 --> 00:20:26,250
You have to break my hand.

372
00:20:26,450 --> 00:20:29,050
Say "all you need is to type in your birth number" and I'll break both.

373
00:20:29,150 --> 00:20:31,170
All you need is to type in your birth number.

374
00:20:31,170 --> 00:20:33,430
Then we'll both feel better.

375
00:20:33,470 --> 00:20:34,390
But this is the left one.

376
00:20:34,390 --> 00:20:34,970
I don't care.

377
00:20:34,990 --> 00:20:35,630
But I do.

378
00:20:35,910 --> 00:20:37,210
The left one is hand number two.

379
00:20:37,510 --> 00:20:38,250
Then the right one.

380
00:20:39,510 --> 00:20:39,990
Bye.

381
00:20:41,650 --> 00:20:42,550
Lock the door properly.

382
00:20:44,300 --> 00:20:45,360
No, what are you doing?

383
00:20:45,560 --> 00:20:46,120
Breaking your hand.

384
00:20:46,200 --> 00:20:47,820
Like this? But it'll hurt.

385
00:20:48,020 --> 00:20:49,380
For crying out loud, you wanted your hand broken, didn't you?

386
00:20:49,520 --> 00:20:51,420
I mean, where does such brutality come from?

387
00:20:51,560 --> 00:20:52,760
So do you want your hand broken or not?

388
00:20:52,940 --> 00:20:55,640
But without anesthesia, you're acting like a butcher.

389
00:20:55,720 --> 00:20:56,600
Then anesthetize yourself somehow.

390
00:21:09,200 --> 00:21:09,560
Ready?

391
00:21:11,650 --> 00:21:12,950
One more spring blend.

392
00:21:22,150 --> 00:21:23,650
Tomas is going to kill me.

393
00:21:24,490 --> 00:21:25,370
Good evening, Simona.

394
00:21:26,010 --> 00:21:27,070
Bruntal called.

395
00:21:27,390 --> 00:21:28,770
We have to leave immediately.

396
00:21:30,070 --> 00:21:32,130
Marcelka, please, could you wait outside for a moment?

397
00:21:32,150 --> 00:21:32,950
I'm here with Simona...

398
00:21:32,950 --> 00:21:34,050
We don't have a minute.

399
00:21:34,190 --> 00:21:37,810
The mayor said the frogs started migrating unexpectedly early this year.

400
00:21:39,150 --> 00:21:40,350
Did you say frogs?

401
00:21:40,950 --> 00:21:42,350
I meant frogs.

402
00:21:42,880 --> 00:21:44,240
We should take the Pulnek route.

403
00:21:44,360 --> 00:21:45,300
That one's still holding.

404
00:21:45,720 --> 00:21:47,640
Then hurry up and go pack.

405
00:21:47,880 --> 00:21:48,720
Do you have motion sickness pills?

406
00:21:49,250 --> 00:21:53,250
The pontoon bridge over the Lobnik has loose ropes.

407
00:21:53,750 --> 00:21:54,450
See?

408
00:21:54,450 --> 00:21:57,450
If you weren't such a coward, you could already be happily howling in pain.

409
00:22:04,250 --> 00:22:08,250
With a stunning triple-chug, Czech competitor Pacovsky has closed the gap from the straw event.

410
00:22:11,950 --> 00:22:18,150
And the thrilling duel between him and the German Fibbinger will be decided by the final royal discipline.

411
00:22:18,150 --> 00:22:18,770
The marathon!

412
00:22:25,950 --> 00:22:29,950
And while the competitors prepare, let's welcome once again Iron Zekon.

413
00:22:44,860 --> 00:22:45,560
Hey.

414
00:22:45,560 --> 00:22:46,650
Who's that?

415
00:22:46,800 --> 00:22:47,860
Iron Zekon.

416
00:22:47,920 --> 00:22:49,260
The strongest guy around.

417
00:22:49,380 --> 00:22:50,080
A looker.

418
00:22:50,450 --> 00:22:52,330
And insanely strong.

419
00:22:52,450 --> 00:22:55,030
We met at the restrooms, he patted my shoulders.

420
00:22:55,030 --> 00:22:57,550
It hurt a bit, but now I can call him Zdenda.

421
00:23:01,050 --> 00:23:06,450
Yeah, he looks like he could have looked at that singer and scared him off.

422
00:23:13,150 --> 00:23:15,550
Sasenka, that's quite a strong man, isn't he?

423
00:23:16,150 --> 00:23:19,680
He's disgusting, he just destroys things, he's a mindless brute.

424
00:23:19,680 --> 00:23:22,680
Well, honey, when a guy thinks, it's about how to fool you.

425
00:23:22,780 --> 00:23:25,140
Your dad for example, now there's a great thinker.

426
00:23:25,300 --> 00:23:26,220
I'd rather read.

427
00:23:26,860 --> 00:23:27,260
Sure.

428
00:23:34,750 --> 00:23:38,540
We ask the competitors to report to the start of the final discipline.

429
00:23:38,540 --> 00:23:50,920
Three competitors are lining up for the marathon.

430
00:23:50,920 --> 00:23:58,140
At table number one, the Czech number one and defending champion, representing the Czech Republic, Franta Ozzak-Pacovsky.

431
00:24:01,550 --> 00:24:06,690
Number two, the challenger from Germany, Herr Heino Fibbinger.

432
00:24:12,950 --> 00:24:16,830
And number three, Enzo Birneri, Italy.

433
00:24:19,650 --> 00:24:23,840
And since Vlada Hron still hasn't come to, the marathon will be started by

434
00:24:23,840 --> 00:24:24,800
Iron Zekon.

435
00:24:24,880 --> 00:24:25,360
So, lads.

436
00:24:25,850 --> 00:24:26,750
Ready.

437
00:24:27,950 --> 00:24:28,850
Set.

438
00:24:31,550 --> 00:24:34,690
Oops, oh dear, I seem to have crushed it.

439
00:24:34,690 --> 00:24:35,750
Well, never mind, lads.

440
00:24:35,870 --> 00:24:36,810
So drink up.

441
00:24:36,870 --> 00:24:37,230
Go.

442
00:24:52,220 --> 00:24:52,700
Ivuska.

443
00:24:53,950 --> 00:24:54,750
Dad, where are you?

444
00:24:54,950 --> 00:24:57,350
They're already on their 21st beer.

445
00:24:57,850 --> 00:25:00,150
I came to say goodbye, I'm going to Bruntal.

446
00:25:00,550 --> 00:25:01,850
You didn't chicken out.

447
00:25:04,050 --> 00:25:10,150
What's that under your coat?

448
00:25:10,550 --> 00:25:11,750
A bulletproof vest.

449
00:25:13,450 --> 00:25:14,550
It's a tough region.

450
00:25:15,250 --> 00:25:17,400
If anything happens to me, I wrote everything down for you.

451
00:25:17,400 --> 00:25:18,220
It's on the fridge.

452
00:25:19,250 --> 00:25:20,440
And say hi to Ozzak.

453
00:25:21,350 --> 00:25:23,450
Dad, Ozzak is heading for victory, won't you wait?

454
00:25:24,450 --> 00:25:26,430
Marcela and Simona are already waiting in the car.

455
00:25:26,430 --> 00:25:26,850
Dad!

456
00:25:28,810 --> 00:25:29,690
Mamma mia!

457
00:25:30,770 --> 00:25:33,930
The Italian competitor ends at the insurmountable 21st beer.

458
00:25:33,930 --> 00:25:35,350
How will this end?

459
00:25:35,370 --> 00:25:37,750
Will the Czechs succumb to Germanic thirst?

460
00:25:39,250 --> 00:25:41,550
22 swigs, dawn is breaking!

461
00:25:46,450 --> 00:25:47,010
OZZAK!

462
00:25:47,410 --> 00:25:47,970
OZZAK!

463
00:25:48,270 --> 00:25:48,830
OZZAK!

464
00:25:49,210 --> 00:25:49,770
OZZAK!

465
00:25:50,030 --> 00:25:50,590
OZZAK!

466
00:25:50,870 --> 00:25:51,430
OZZAK!

467
00:25:51,550 --> 00:25:52,150
OZZAK!

468
00:26:07,430 --> 00:26:09,210
Tomas, we said five minutes.

469
00:26:09,470 --> 00:26:10,810
I'm coming, sorry.

470
00:26:11,190 --> 00:26:11,750
Please.

471
00:26:11,930 --> 00:26:13,450
I've got nothing left to lose.

472
00:26:34,440 --> 00:26:35,000
Laika.

473
00:26:39,250 --> 00:26:40,550
The winning competitor may savor the honorary beer.

474
00:26:41,940 --> 00:26:42,500
Congratulations.

475
00:26:42,680 --> 00:26:43,980
Oh, pardon.

476
00:26:44,360 --> 00:26:44,920
Thanks, Zdenda.

477
00:26:59,440 --> 00:27:01,420
Tomas, we're half an hour behind schedule.

478
00:27:01,500 --> 00:27:02,780
We're almost past Malicek.

479
00:27:03,020 --> 00:27:03,360
All right.

480
00:27:04,050 --> 00:27:04,650
Bro.

481
00:27:05,250 --> 00:27:08,150
You showed me the way, that I shouldn't give up.

482
00:27:08,950 --> 00:27:10,850
I'll handle Bruntal, let's go!

483
00:27:11,550 --> 00:27:14,150
Wait, you're going to Bruntal?

484
00:27:14,300 --> 00:27:16,440
Yeah, I've got an encore there.

485
00:27:16,620 --> 00:27:17,840
You must be one tough guy.

486
00:27:17,960 --> 00:27:19,960
I never dared go further than Krnov.

487
00:27:20,550 --> 00:27:21,950
That's still pretty lucky.

488
00:27:22,400 --> 00:27:23,000
Bye!

489
00:27:24,550 --> 00:27:25,710
Oh crap, again?

490
00:27:25,710 --> 00:27:27,770
That's it, that's it.

491
00:27:28,050 --> 00:27:30,130
At least three, just the wrist.

492
00:27:30,130 --> 00:27:31,270
That's too much.

493
00:27:32,070 --> 00:27:33,990
I'm not going anywhere, it's broken.

494
00:27:54,150 --> 00:27:54,700
Thirty-two.

495
00:27:59,050 --> 00:28:00,950
You still haven't gone to the bathroom?

496
00:28:03,550 --> 00:28:05,050
One more will fit in there.

497
00:28:23,950 --> 00:28:24,650
Vera.

498
00:28:25,350 --> 00:28:26,850
Oh, hi Vlasta.

499
00:28:28,450 --> 00:28:29,750
I'm looking at it too.

500
00:28:31,350 --> 00:28:32,350
What does it say?

501
00:28:33,050 --> 00:28:36,250
Carbon-based beings, you will be destroyed.

502
00:28:37,450 --> 00:28:39,350
And there's a countdown in the bottom corner.

503
00:28:40,450 --> 00:28:41,250
You too?

504
00:28:42,550 --> 00:28:43,380
Well, okay then.

505
00:28:43,380 --> 00:28:44,020
Bye.
